ntic to the Mississippi. In response, Indians created one of the most important temperance movements in American history, a movement that was nevertheless unable to halt the lucrative commerce.The author follows the trail of rum from the West Indian producers to the colonial distributors and on to the Indian consumers in the eastern woodlands. To discover why Indians participated in the trade and why they experienced such a powerful desire for alcohol, he addresses current medical views on alcoholism and reexamines the colonial era as a time when Indians were forming new strategies for survival in a world that had been radically changed. Finally, Mancall compares Indian drinking in New France and New Spain with that in the British colonies.Forever shattering the stereotype of the drunken Indian, Mancall offers a powerful indictment of English participation in the liquor trade and a new awareness or the trade's tragic cost for the American Indians.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Mrz 2024) 4aMedicine & Medical Issues. 4aNative American Studies. 4aU.S. History.  aIndian drinking.  aIndian-European relations.  aIndians of North America and their alcohol use.  aIndigenous Peoples in the Americas history.  aIndigenous Peoples.  aIndigenous cultures.  aalcholism and indigenous people.  aalcohol abuse in native american communities.  aalcohol consumption in colonial era.  aamerican history.  aamerican indian culture and research.  abooks on native american history.  abritish liquor trade in the americas.  acolonial indian affairs.  acolonial native american history.  acolonial period history.  acolonial records and indian affairs.  aeffects of alcohol on american indians.  aeffects of alcohol on native americans.  aethnohistory.  agene that causes alcoholism.  ahistory of alcohol use.  aho